00:46:46.890 --> 00:46:48.350
I really don't.

00:46:48.350 --> 00:46:52.150
I've been asked this question
since the last eight years.

00:46:52.150 --> 00:46:55.280
I still don't have
an answer for it.

00:46:55.280 --> 00:46:58.020
It keeps changing
also, in all honesty.

00:46:58.020 --> 00:47:01.510
But eventually, at
the end of it all,

00:47:01.510 --> 00:47:03.540
it's all about
engaging with people.

00:47:03.540 --> 00:47:05.560
It's all about
entertaining people,

00:47:05.560 --> 00:47:10.180
and hopefully getting
them to do good things.

00:47:10.180 --> 00:47:13.810
So it's very difficult
to say which one.

00:47:13.810 --> 00:47:15.481
I, too, I enjoy all of it.

00:47:15.481 --> 00:47:17.230
And the minute I stop
enjoying [? doing ?]

00:47:17.230 --> 00:47:18.294
film, I'll stop doing it.

00:47:18.294 --> 00:47:19.210
So that's [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:21.300
AUDIENCE: I feel like your
ideas are really important,

00:47:21.300 --> 00:47:22.530
and I've learned a lot today.

00:47:22.530 --> 00:47:25.420
Do you have any intention
in making a film geared

00:47:25.420 --> 00:47:26.890
towards the American audiences?

00:47:29.830 --> 00:47:35.000
FARHAN AKHTAR: I don't really
think of film like that,

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:37.970
to be honest with you.

00:47:37.970 --> 00:47:40.880
What happens is,
as an artist, you

00:47:40.880 --> 00:47:45.160
get excited by either what's
offered to you as a script,

00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:47.610
or then an idea that you have.

00:47:47.610 --> 00:47:50.400
And on some level,
we are, I guess,

00:47:50.400 --> 00:47:52.910
bound by the constraints,
for whatever it's worth,

00:47:52.910 --> 00:47:54.410
at least in the
mainstream in India,

00:47:54.410 --> 00:47:57.680
by the language that we
have to make our film in.

00:47:57.680 --> 00:47:59.620
So there's a certain
challenge that

00:47:59.620 --> 00:48:02.410
comes with taking that
across to an audience that

00:48:02.410 --> 00:48:05.500
maybe would watch it if it
was an hour, hour an a half.

00:48:05.500 --> 00:48:07.900
But our films tend to be longer.

00:48:07.900 --> 00:48:09.140
They do.

00:48:09.140 --> 00:48:10.265
That's a fact.

00:48:10.265 --> 00:48:12.710
Also, culturally different
because of the song and dance.

00:48:12.710 --> 00:48:16.280
So it becomes somehow maybe
not taken as seriously

00:48:16.280 --> 00:48:19.130
because of that aspect of it.

00:48:19.130 --> 00:48:22.960
But the hope really is that
it could reach out to anyone.

00:48:22.960 --> 00:48:25.300
We watch foreign language
films all the time.

00:48:25.300 --> 00:48:27.185
We watch them with
subtitles, and at no point

00:48:27.185 --> 00:48:28.560
do we feel like,
oh, I don't want

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:32.700
to watch that film because it's
in Korean, or it's in Spanish,

00:48:32.700 --> 00:48:33.882
or it's in English.

00:48:33.882 --> 00:48:35.840
You don't feel like you
don't want to watch it.

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:38.980
So hopefully we can excite
people to watch our films

00:48:38.980 --> 00:48:40.900
for what they are.

00:48:40.900 --> 00:48:43.030
And it's of course
an understanding

00:48:43.030 --> 00:48:48.031
that you'd want it to have some
substance that could resonate

00:48:48.031 --> 00:48:48.780
with those people.

00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:51.560
That I do understand
and appreciate.

00:48:51.560 --> 00:48:56.040
But I feel that a film
like "Zindagi Na Milegi

00:48:56.040 --> 00:49:00.410
Dobara," for example, I feel
that if marketed correctly

00:49:00.410 --> 00:49:06.150
to a viewer that does not speak
Hindi, it would affect them.

00:49:06.150 --> 00:49:08.430
It would influence them.

00:49:08.430 --> 00:49:10.000
They'd enjoy that film.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:14.850
So the challenge of marketing
it then lies with somebody else.

00:49:14.850 --> 00:49:17.670
And hopefully that is
something that we can track,

00:49:17.670 --> 00:49:20.950
because that is an area I feel
that Hindi films have still

00:49:20.950 --> 00:49:25.750
not found they feed on, on how
to make it exciting for people

00:49:25.750 --> 00:49:30.255
who are not Indian, or
not from the sub-Continent

00:49:30.255 --> 00:49:32.120
to be able to come in
and enjoy their work.

00:49:34.750 --> 00:49:38.600
ANANT SHUKLA: Great,
so last question.

00:49:38.600 --> 00:49:43.940
Favorite dialogue from a
movie or a poem, a few words

00:49:43.940 --> 00:49:44.650
to leave us with.

00:49:44.650 --> 00:49:48.160
FARHAN AKHTAR: Good
[? shot. ?] So I

00:49:48.160 --> 00:49:52.230
guess I'll leave you all with
maybe the MARD poem, since we

00:49:52.230 --> 00:49:53.420
will hear about that.

00:49:53.420 --> 00:49:54.955
So this is what we
really go around,

00:49:54.955 --> 00:50:01.420
and when we talk about a
blueprint for the new man is--

00:50:01.420 --> 00:50:52.870
